bug.short_desc: Link/Node resolution heuristics considered harmful

long_desc.thetext:
2.0M3. While trying to get EMOF.ecore to generate diagrams I hit a 100% mis-identification of 2 nodes as links and 0% of links as nodes.
? is it common to for links to be explicitly modeled ? - isn't it like Association Classes - possible but rare ? is the number of successful link identifications greater than the node mis-identifications ? - I doubt it. ? is the vocabulary policy multi-lingual? - certainly not. ? are smart (stupid) heuristics a good idea? - yes if you like paper-clip-style help assistants
The code would be much simpler, and the behaviour much more predictable if all attempts to identify links were abandoned. The user then has the simple requirement of promoting all explicitly modeled links to links. At present all nodes and links must be checked for mis-heuristics, since many link identifications are bogus, and some link identifuications may be missed.
Iff link identfication is really necessary, it should occur only for very positive identification of context AND vocabulary. The current code in StructureResolver.resolve has a three-way pre-identification as a node and then a fall-through to a link for anything else.

You may always press 'Deselect All' button and manually decide what will be node and what will be link. Heuristics are not perfect and never will be; they work fair enough for simple models and help to boost diagram editors development. So they will remain.

Deselect All requires explicit definition of everything.
I am suggesting that the heuristic be modified to select all contained classes as nodes, on the basis that node/link discrimination is hard and that consequently more classes will be misclassified as links, than are those that are correctly classified.
Perhaps replacing the 'defaults' button by a variety of heuristic activators:
'Set reachable classes as nodes' 'Set reachable classes as nodes/links'
[with an extension point for more custom heuristics?]
might do the trick

I don't think that someone will write extensions to resolver taking into account that this is a do-it-once step; adding more buttons will make ui more complicated while this is not an editor - it's simple wizard to run once to create initial model.

At the moment it's a simple wizard, but it could evolve, particularly if some useful but poorly integrated third party tool generated stylised Ecore models. There may therefore be a requirement to automatically deduce standardised GMFgraph and GMFtool from Ecore models with a distinctive characteristic - possibly an annotation, possibly a referenced model.
There is a transformation from the Ecore model to the Pattern model. The wizard is an editor for the Pattern model. Then there is a transformation that merges Ecore and Pattern models to produce GMFgraph or GMFtool models. (It would be nice if the Pattern model was shared not duplicated). Until M2M transformation languages mature, the above transformations are sensibly written in bespoke Java.
As well as standarised transformation, I see more patterns. For instance an EClass can be classified as Canvas-Node, Top-Level-Node, Top-Level-Link or Unmodeled as at present, or a Compartment-Node or a Compartment-Node-or-Top-Level-Link (e.g. a nested UML class that may be drawn nested within its parent, or self-standing) or ... An EClass with alterative containers may be independently classified for each container.
I'm not sure whether to start a separate Bugzilla for this... In order to support nested containment with containment drawn as links rather than hierachical positioning (node-on-canvas, or compartment-on-node) it should be possible for the Canvas to have no associated domain element. The generated editor supports an extended Ecore model in which an additional _Root_ Class is added that may contain all other classes. The Canvas may then map the _Root_ and contain all elements that lack properly drawn containments. The validator therefore diagnoses inadequately drawn containment, rather than the editor generation process prohibiting the generation of such an editor. At present it is not possible to use the wizard to generate an editor for a model with nested containment or for one with a manually added _Root_.
I would like the wizard to allow a choice of an EClass as the Canvas mapping, and/or a synthesised _Root_ class. This could sensibly occur on the main pattern editing page so that selecting EClass XXX as Canvas-Node automatically greys out all unreachable EClasses rather than leaving them confusingly blank.
I would like the wizard to offer an extensible combo box of patterns for each EClass.
I think abstract classes could usefully offer an inheritable pattern for their attributes so that label features are automatically shared.
For large models it would be good if the EStructuralFeatures could fold.
I am happy to take a shot at contributing some of this, but obviously there is no point if the above ideas conflict with GMF plans.

bug.short_desc: [Progress] ProgressManager doesn't remove job from jobs hash map

long_desc.thetext:
Build ID: M20060921-0945
Steps To Reproduce: 1. Install Eclipse 3.2.1 M20060921-0945 2. Install on top EMF/XSD 2.1.1 from http://download.eclipse.org/tools/emf/downloads/drops/2.2.2/M200612140300/emf-sdo-xsd-SDK-M200612140300.zip and TPTP-4.2.2-200612191126 from http://www.eclipse.org/downloads/download.php?file=/tptp/4.2.2/dev/TPTP-4.2.2-200612191126/tptp.sdk-TPTP-4.2.2-200612191126.zip. 3. Launch the workbench and from the main menu choose File->Import->Profiling and Logging->Log file 4. In the import log wizard choose Add and select to import the Apache access log file attached to this defect. 5. Click Finish to start importing the Apache log file and swithc to the "Profiling and Logging" perspective when asked. Notice the "Importing log file..." job label displayed on the status bar. If this status label is cleared try to import again the same log file and choose to replace the previously imported one. Notice that this time the status label doesn't go away although the job has finished. Sometimes the status label doesn't get cleared on the first log import.
More information: I did some investigation and found out that the culprit for the label not being cleared is the fact that org.eclipse.ui.internal.progress.ProgressManager is not removing the import log job from it's jobs hash map in the method public void done(IJobChangeEvent event), part of the JobChangeAdapter created in */ private void createChangeListener() { changeListener = new JobChangeAdapter() {...} Not sure why this is happening only for this particular job. The problem is that all the subsequent import log jobs are not cleared and this is causing a memory leak which could become problematic. The org.eclipse.ui.internal.progress.ProgressCanvasViewer is using the org.eclipse.ui.internal.progress.ProgressViewerContentProvider and this one is using the org.eclipse.ui.internal.progress.ProgressManager to get it's content. This is the reason why the import log job name keeps getting displayed.

Created an attachment (id=56232) Sample Apache access log
Attaching a sample Apache access log file required for reproducing the problem.
Changing sev to major since the problem is causing a memory leak which could potentially be troublesome.

The issue is in ImportLogWizard - you are calling done on the progress monitor after the job is finished so I am getting a request for info after I removed it from the cache.
I'll need to see the source of this to see what the issue is but it looks like you are calling done() after the progress monitor is no longer valid

OK, I think I see the problem, but still I think this is a bit strange since I am pretty sure it didn't happen in previous releases of Eclipse. The same client code worked in Eclipse 3.1. I agree the clients have to be careful not to call done() on an "invalid" monitor, but would it be not good practice if also the Eclipse code, to be on the safe side, would ensure that initialization of the job info happens only on a valid monitor? Can you assign this defect to me please, i.e. apnan@ca.ibm.com. I have verified that by removing the unnecessary done() the problem dissapears. Thanks for your time and sorry for the inconvenience that this issue may have caused you.
Bob has retired and I cannot assign this defect to myself unfortunately.
Assign to Alex as requested

And in continuation of what I said before, according to the java doc of the IProgressMonitor interface, the done() method may be called more then once, implementations should be prepared to handle this case.

We certainly should protect against this - please feel free to log me a bug if you like.
We should also specify in the javadoc of Job that the monitor should not be used outside of the life of the job
The problem is very similar to bug 149857.. the fix for that bug only fixed the case where isCanceled is called after the job completes, rather than fixing the general problem.
I have opened https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=172327 for this issue. Not sure if Platform.UI is the right component though.
Fixed.

bug.short_desc: Add a BOM provider

long_desc.thetext:
Replaces bug # 169196 The idea is to allow encapsulation of constraints introduced by a CQuery in a reusable way. There could be problems by just following dependencies and versions and normally such issues are dealt with in the Cquery. If however someone resolves lots of problems and creates an elaborate CQuery for part of the resulting graph, all users wanting the same subgraph would have to state the same constraints in their CQueries - thus all complexity bubbles up to the surface and the very problem Buckminster tries to help with was just transformed into a different shape.
If instead, it is possible to represent a component with a complete resolution in the form of a BOM, it is possible to use such a BOM instead of resolving this part of the subgraph - i.e. use a canned resolution. Although it lacks in flexibility/dynamics, it effectively makes it easier to reuse someone elses configuration.
So, if Component A has a dependency on B, and it is known that just resolving B produces a no-good configuration (without judicious use of advisor nodes in the CQuery for A) but there is a pre-made B BOM (oh-glorious-working-b.bom) it should be possible to state in the RMAP that this BOM can be used instead of the component itself.
The idea is to implement a Provider (BOM Provider) that simply can look inside of a BOM file and return the embedded CSPEC for the top component AND the full resolution graph. The resolver if it finds what it is looking for by consulting this reader (i.-e. it finds B inside the oh-glorious... file) it accepts that has having found B, and takes the rest of the BOM as the resolution of B.
This is a better mechanism that what was proposed in Replaces bug # 169196, and that issue has now been closed.

We now have a component type called "bom" and another called "cquery". The former deals with exported Bill Of Materials in and the latter with Component Queries. Used together with the "url" reader, they will both resolve to a Bill Of Materials that is hooked into the overall resolution graph.
Available since version 1.0.0.v20070122

bug.short_desc: Diagram.notation.type should be globally unique

long_desc.thetext:
ecore_diagram currently has the diagram notation type "Ecore", since gmfgen defaults to a simple name based on the model.
It would be better if this name was "org.eclipse.gmf.ecore.editor.Ecore".
The current policy of model-based rather than editor-based naming may cause confusion wherever multiple GMF-based editors are offered by various 'vendors' for the same model.
I fell over this when I copied org.eclipse.gmf.ecore.editor.Ecore to MyEcoreEditor, changing all usages of org.eclipse.gmf.ecore.editor. Since I has failed to rename "Ecore" to perhaps "MyEcore", I had two "Ecore" editors and so the wrong set of EditParts got created.
My stupidity/mistake would have been avoided if the diagram type had been "org.eclipse.gmf.ecore.editor.Ecore".
My mistake is just unfortunate. The need to set a sound precedent that diagram notation types are globally unique is worth encouraging.
Perhaps, this should be aligned with single editor/plugin/domain id we talked some time ago?
